main event: On 16-17 May 1958 in Drummond, Wisconsin, a civilian reported a round, white object the size of a nickel, which appeared bright and twinkling, and was initially thought to be a star. However, there was insufficient data for evaluation, and the conclusion was that it was an astronomical star.
interesting points: The object was initially thought to be an astronomical star, but there was uncertainty due to insufficient data for evaluation.
The observer reported seeing a round, white object the size of a nickel, which appeared bright and twinkling, and was stationary.
The report mentions that the object was still visible for approximately 1-1/2 hours.
Although photos were taken, they failed to show the object. The photographs were examined and deemed to show developing streaks, fuzziness, and no identifiable subject other than tree tops.
The sighting was passed on to the 31st Air Division for review and coordination with the Director of Intelligence.
sighted object: Round, white object the size of a nickel
